Polynomial Regression

  • Simple linear regression model can be extended in many ways…

  • Can include higher order terms

\[Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1x_i + \beta_2x_i^2+E_i\]

  • Still use lm()
    • add "main effect" higher order terms with I(var^k)
    • can use poly(var, degree, raw = TRUE)
    • without raw = TRUE centered variables are used
quadFit <- lm(dist ~ speed + I(speed^2), cars)

Polynomial Regression

quadFit <- lm(dist ~ speed + I(speed^2), cars)

Polynomial Regression

ggplot(cars, aes(x = speed, y = dist)) + geom_point() +
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", formula = y ~ x + I(x^2))

Polynomial Regression

  • Prediction can still be done with predict()
predict(quadFit, newdata = data.frame(speed = c(4, 25)), interval = "confidence")
##         fit       lwr      upr
## 1  7.722637 -8.665329  24.1106
## 2 87.776892 74.782756 100.7710

Polynomial Regression

  • Add PI easily added with ciTools
cars <- datasets::cars %>% ciTools::add_pi(quadFit, names = c("lower", "upper"))
ggplot(cars, aes(x = speed, y = dist)) +
    geom_point() + 
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", formula = y ~ x + I(x^2), fill = "Blue") +
    geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = lower, ymax = upper), alpha = 0.3, fill = "Red") +
    ggtitle("Scatter Plot with 95% PI")

Multiple Linear Regression

  • Simple linear regression model can be extended in many ways…

  • Can include more explanatory variables and/or higher order terms

Ex:

\[Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1x_{1i} + \beta_2x_{2i} + \beta_3x_{1i}x_{2i}+E_i\]

  • Still use lm()
    • add "main effect" terms with + name
    • interactions with + name1:name2
    • all possible combinations with + name1*name2
  • Still fit by minimizing sum of squared errors

Multiple Linear Regression

  • Consider data on voting preferences by county
    • Use pct with college degree & population change in county to predict county level income
voting <- tbl_df(read.csv("../datasets/counties.csv", header = TRUE))

Multiple Linear Regression

  • Fit "best" plane through points

\[E(Income) = \beta_0 + \beta_1*(Per College) + \beta_2*(Pop Change)\]

  • Fit "best" saddle through the points

\[E(Income) = \beta_0 + \beta_1*(Per College) +\] \[ \beta_2*(Pop Change) + \beta_3*(Per Income)*(Pop Change)\]

Multiple Linear Regression

fit <- lm(income ~ pop.change + college, data = subVoting)
#set up prediction explanatory variables
grid.lines = 40
x.pred <- seq(min(subVoting$pop.change), max(subVoting$pop.change), length.out = grid.lines)
y.pred <- seq(min(subVoting$college), max(subVoting$college), length.out = grid.lines)
xy <- expand.grid(pop.change = x.pred, college = y.pred)
#predictions
z.pred <- matrix(predict(fit, newdata = xy), 
                                 nrow = grid.lines, ncol = grid.lines)
# scatter plot with regression plane (rgl package)
plot3d(x = subVoting$pop.change, y = subVoting$college, z = subVoting$income,
                    cex = 0.8, theta = 20, phi = 20, ticktype = "detailed",
                    xlab = "Pop Change", ylab = "Per College", zlab = 
"Income")
#add surface
surface3d(x = x.pred, y = y.pred, z = z.pred, color = "green")

With an Interaction Term and Quadratic Terms

fit <- lm(income ~ pop.change + college + pop.change:college +

Including a Categorical Predictor

  • May want fits that differ by the level of a variable
  • Often better to do in one model fit
  • Here a common slope is assumed
  • R uses the first level of the categorical variable as a reference level
regionFit <- lm(income ~ college + region, data = voting)
regionFit

Including a Categorical Predictor

  • Intercept really represents estimated average income for Midwest with 0 percent college

\[Est~Midwest~Income = 19584.1 + 718.6*(Per College)\]

  • If you want to predict for the Northeast, include that coefficient in the intercept

\[Est~Northeast~Income = 19584.1 +3100.9 + 718.6*(Per College)\]
